    <p>Chad's observation cuts to the core of why travel is a protein problem even for experienced, health-conscious men. It's not that the food isn't available — protein exists at every airport, every hotel, every restaurant chain in America. The problem is visibility. At home, your routine creates automatic awareness. On the road, that autopilot disappears.</p>

    <p>The solution isn't a complicated travel nutrition plan. It's knowing your anchor options at the places you actually end up — and having a few backup items in your bag for when the day goes sideways.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>Why Travel Kills Protein Intake — The Real Reason</h2>

    <p>Most men who track their protein at home and go dark for three days of travel don't come back having eaten terribly. They come back having eaten inconsistently — a big protein dinner one night, an airport sandwich the next, a hotel continental breakfast that was mostly carbs. The meals weren't bad. The distribution was.</p>

    <p>Remember the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-pacing-strategy-men-over-40/">protein pacing principle</a>: muscle protein synthesis is triggered per meal, not per day. Three days of skipping the 30g threshold at breakfast and lunch — even if dinner is solid — means three days of primarily catabolic mornings and afternoons. For a man over 40 already managing <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a>, that compounds fast.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <div class="warning-label">The Travel Trap</div>
      <p>A hotel continental breakfast (pastry, orange juice, small yogurt) might hit 12–15g of protein. An airport lunch grabbed between gates (sandwich wrap, bag of chips) might hit 20g. By 3pm on day one you're already 30–40g behind your daily target with only dinner left to close the gap. Dinner can't fully compensate — and the next morning the pattern repeats.</p>
    </div>

