    <!-- THE TRACKING POINT -->
    <h2>Why Tracking Matters More on the Road Than at Home</h2>

    <p>Chad Moeller put it simply: at home, he knows his numbers cold. His routine does the tracking for him. On the road, the routine is gone — and without visibility, even an experienced, health-informed man loses track of where he stands.</p>

    <p>This is exactly the scenario SnapProtein was built for. Not the days when everything is controlled and familiar — those days take care of themselves. The app pays off most on the days when you're at an airport at 9am, deciding between a granola bar and a jerky bag, and you want to know whether you've already cleared your morning threshold or you're still 15g short from a light hotel breakfast.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>The two-tap rule on the road:</strong> Every time you eat something, log it before you move on. On travel days, meals blur together and memory gets unreliable fast. Logging in real time — not reconstructing at the end of the day — is the difference between knowing your number and guessing it. See <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what 120g of protein actually looks like</a> as a reference point for your daily target.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The One Restaurant Move That Changes Everything</h2>

    <p>If there's one ordering habit worth building for travel, it's this: <strong>ask for double protein, or ask to swap a starch side for extra protein.</strong> At almost every sit-down restaurant in America, you can swap fries for a side salad, add an extra egg to a breakfast plate, or request a double portion of the grilled chicken for a small upcharge.</p>

    <p>A 6oz chicken breast becomes an 8oz. A two-egg omelet becomes a three-egg omelet. A steak dinner that was tracking at 35g becomes 45g. These aren't dietary restrictions — they're straightforward customizations that any kitchen can handle and most waitstaff expect from health-conscious diners.</p>

    <p>Men who travel frequently and consistently hit their protein targets almost always have this habit. It's the single highest-leverage move available at a restaurant table.</p>

